05:56.800 --> 06:00.780
Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu spoke to the U.S. Congress again

06:00.780 --> 06:05.220
yesterday. He's given addresses to Congress four different times, which is

06:05.220 --> 06:08.620
more than any foreign leader in history. He's been around for a while.

06:09.220 --> 06:13.860
Netanyahu's latest yesterday included flourishes often seen in a

06:13.860 --> 06:17.420
presidential state-of-the-union address. He told stories of guests in the

06:17.420 --> 06:22.400
audience to illustrate and defend Israel's war against Hamas. For the

06:22.400 --> 06:28.360
forces of civilization to triumph, America and Israel must stand together.

06:29.420 --> 06:32.760
Today, the Prime Minister meets President Biden at the White House and also

06:32.760 --> 06:38.120
meets with Vice President Harris how she engages Netanyahu matters more now

06:38.120 --> 06:41.520
that she's running for president. NPR White House correspondent Asma Khaled

06:41.520 --> 06:44.380
is with us now to tell us more about that. Good morning, Asma. Good

06:44.380 --> 06:47.740
morning. I wanted to ask you how you characterize the Vice President's

06:47.740 --> 06:50.720
policies on Gaza. I mean, obviously, she's the Vice President, so you

06:50.720 --> 06:55.840
assume that her policies would have to be in lockstep with the presidents.

06:56.520 --> 07:00.380
But what would you say about how she approaches the issue? Well, the

07:00.380 --> 07:03.960
substance of what she's saying is similar to Biden, but she differs in

07:03.960 --> 07:08.800
style and tone. Harris did describe her as having a, quote, unwavering

07:08.800 --> 07:12.580
commitment to the security of Israel. I also talked with an advisor from

07:12.580 --> 07:16.080
Harris's days in the Senate, Hailey Soyfer, who told me what it was like at

07:16.080 --> 07:19.100
a recent White House event in which she saw the Vice President take on a

07:19.100 --> 07:22.620
real leadership role in condemning the use of sexual violence in the

07:22.620 --> 07:26.100
October 7th attacks. But really, Michelle, the real difference from Biden

07:26.100 --> 07:30.200
is how Harris talks about people in Gaza. Take a listen to her comments

07:30.200 --> 07:34.780
from this past March in Selma, Alabama. What we are seeing every day in

07:34.780 --> 07:41.400
Gaza is devastating. We have seen reports of families eating leaves or

07:41.400 --> 07:49.140
animal feed. Women giving birth to malnourished babies with little or no

07:49.140 --> 07:52.840
medical care. I've spoken with multiple people who've remarked to me that

07:52.840 --> 07:57.200
Harris shows a greater degree of empathy for Palestinian civilians than

07:57.200 --> 08:01.200
they have heard publicly from Biden. Have these words affected how voters

08:01.200 --> 08:05.720
see her? Well, people I've spoken with in the Arab-American community say

08:05.720 --> 08:10.660
that Harris is not viewed as being as toxic as Biden. I was speaking to

08:10.660 --> 08:14.580
Rubel Roman. She's a Democratic Georgia state legislator, a Palestinian

08:14.580 --> 08:18.200
American, and she put it this way. I can tell you right now that if I had,

08:18.300 --> 08:22.400
for example, tried to go to a mosque or Arab community event and urged them

08:22.400 --> 08:26.620
to vote for Joe Biden, I would never be invited back. The anger was so deep

08:26.620 --> 08:31.880
and the hurt was so deep. Even for me, I tell people that. And I think

08:31.880 --> 08:35.980
people would at least be open to hearing from her and to let her make her

08:35.980 --> 08:40.180
case. And some Democrats who voted uncommitted during the primaries told me

08:40.180 --> 08:42.980
that they're willing to give Harris a chance. I mean, to be clear, they are

08:42.980 --> 08:46.520
not saying they will definitively vote for her, but there's a possibility.

08:47.140 --> 08:50.100
I'll also say that Harris was one of the earlier people in the

08:50.100 --> 08:53.580
administration to show a less dismissive response to some of the protests

08:53.580 --> 08:56.900
here at home. Today, she is meeting separately with Israel's Prime

08:56.900 --> 09:01.440
Minister, separately from Biden. What do you expect from her meeting? What

09:01.440 --> 09:04.740
I'm watching for is how closely she sticks to the president. You know, she

09:04.740 --> 09:08.040
inherits this problem now in her campaign and following the attack in

09:08.040 --> 09:12.420
October that killed more than 1,200 people. There are now more than 39,000

09:12.420 --> 09:15.920
Palestinians who've been killed and there's still no ceasefire. And some

09:15.920 --> 09:19.200
people will blame her because she is a part of this administration. She has

09:19.200 --> 09:23.440
a real delicate balancing act where she's going to try not to alienate

09:23.440 --> 09:27.500
supporters of Israel who make up a key part of the Democratic Party, but

09:27.500 --> 09:30.940
she's also trying to win back some of the young, progressive, brown and

09:30.940 --> 09:34.320
black voters whom Biden alienated with some of his decisions about this

09:34.320 --> 09:38.640
war. That is NPR's Asma Khaled. Asma, thank you. Good to talk to you.

